<br>
If a man commits a crime, then knowingly takes a drug that causes him to forget the crime, is he innocent?  Let's assume that the drug erases all memory of premeditation as well as the act.  Also assume that the person is not entirely &quot;bad&quot;, in that he could be an average joe that for some reason, under unordinary circumstances, commits a heinous crime.  Say this circumstance is unlikely to happen again.  To put it simply - it was a crime of passion that could have happened to anybody:  this particular man was no more susceptable to it than anybody else.<br>
<br>
So, what do you think?  Is he innocent or guilty?  Both from a legal, and moral standpoint.  If it can be proven in court with 100% certainty that this man has no idea that he committed this crime, or why he committed, should he be aquitted?  If he is standing at the gates of heaven, should he be judged for what he did?<br>
<br>
Keep in mind a few things.  First, this was not an accident, he knowingly destroyed his memory for this VERY purpose.  Second, put yourself in his situation.  You wake up one day, no different than the last, and suddenly you are facing life in prison for something you have no clue happened, and you scream to the very end that you are innocent.<br>
<br>
I think this is hard as hell to say one way or the other, but I am leaning towards innocent, morally at least, and within a lot of grey area legally too.<br>
<br>
-Takkon <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gyreredbranch>Gyre Redbranch</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/12/03 3:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2007.topic&index=1>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Guilty or Innocent?</span><hr size=1> I find this one easy -- guilty.<br>
<br>
Taking the 'forget stuff' drug doesn't mitigate the actual damage done by the crime.  Nor does taking the drug somehow cleanse him of whatever caused him to be a criminal.  It simply erased his memory of the incident.<br>
<br>
We don't lock up criminals because they remember what they did.  We lock up criminals because of the fact of what they did (punishment) and the danger that they may do it again (protection of society).  A poor memory, drug-induced or not, addresses neither issue.<br>
<br>
Stating that it was a 'crime of passion' that anyone could have committed has nothing to do with the drug.  That calls into question whether anyone should be convicted of your hypothetical defense, regardless of whether they remember it.<br>
<br>
Finally, if such a drug existed, and if the &quot;I don't remember&quot; defense worked... well, this is a pretty steep slide, as slippery slopes go. <p>Hunter Gyre Redbranch<br>

