<br>
<br>
Really, drop the part between the commas to get the real question.  &quot;If a man commits a crime, is he innocent?&quot;<br>
<br>
What he does to assuage his personal feelings of guilt is irrelevent.  Either he did commit the crime, in which case he is guilty, or he didn't, in which case he is innocent.  While, from his standpoint, it is unjust, because he does not remember doing it, the victims are no less victimized for his inability to remember it.  <br>
<br>
Also, ponder the ramifications of saying that if you can't remember it, you aren't guilty.  Suddenly everyone keeps a stock on hand.  I decide one day, I really need money.  I go rob a bank and take a memory-erasing drug.  Not guilty your honor.  Sure that certainly seems to be me on the videotape shooting the teller, but I don't remember a thing.  I'm free?  Thank you.  These pills are great!<br>
<br>
For an interesting story with similar theme, I highly recommend &quot;How it was when the past went away&quot; by Robert Silverberg.  Terrorist drops a memory destroying drug in a city's water supply.  A very good read.<br>
